<DOC><DOCNO> AP880621-0153 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-21-88 1356EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Manigat-Haiti     06-21 0231</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Manigat-Haiti,0237</SECOND><HEAD>Manigat Calls For International Isolation of Haiti</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ousted President LeslieManigat of Haiti called today for international isolation ofHaiti's new military government.   Manigat, ousted in a military coup Monday and put on a plane tothe Dominican Republic, called the new regime ``very fragile'' andblamed the coup on corruption in the military.   Manigat told reporters in Santo Domingo that he has talked toforeign governments and international organizations asking them toreject the government named Monday by Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, thearmed forces chief.   Manigat, a 57-year-old former political scientist, was electedin controversial, fraud-marked voting Jan. 17. He said he hasn'tdecided where his place of exile will be, but he plans to travelthis month to Europe for meetings with political leaders to rallyopposition to the new government.   The first he knew of the Namphy coup was as he sat in his homewatching the state television Monday, Manigat said.   Manigat said he wasn't told where he was being sent until helanded in the Dominican Republic, which shares the island ofHispaniola with Haiti.   Manigat had rescinded Namphy's order retiring and transferringmilitary officers last week. He had placed Namphy under housearrest, but his troops freed him late Sunday and Namphy took thenational palace and announced a new government Monday.</TEXT></DOC>